#removing outliers greater than upper fence for S_Degree
Q1 = med_fin['S_Degree'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = med_fin['S_Degree'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1    #IQR is interquartile range. 

filter = (med_fin['S_Degree'] <= Q3 + 1.5 *IQR)
#filter
med_fin = med_fin.loc[filter]

In [68]:
# empty list that will hold accuracy scores
ac_scores = []

# perform accuracy metrics for values from 1,3,5....49
for k in range(1,20,2):
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
    # predict the response
    y_pred = knn.predict(X_test)
    # evaluate accuracy
    scores = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    ac_scores.append(scores)

# subsetting just the odd ones
neighbors = list(range(1,20,2))

# changing to misclassification error
MSE = [1 - x for x in ac_scores]

# determining best k
optimal_k = neighbors[MSE.index(min(MSE))]
print("The optimal number of neighbors is %d" % optimal_k)

The optimal number of neighbors is 1

from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

# fitting the model

# predict the response
y_pred = knn.predict(X_test)

# evaluate accuracy

Conclusion¶

  1. We can see the TP rates in the above confusion matrix is quite high.
  2. Thus with k = 1, Standard scaled data gives highest accuracy and min MSE.
  3. S_slope as its highly positively correlated to P_incidence and highly negatively correlated to P_radius its removed.
  4. S_Degree is highly correlated with P_incidence but not removed as its highly correlated to Class variable.
  5. All the rest of attributes other than P_radius were quite contributive to the class variables.

Suggestions¶

  1. The class variable values basically did not convey a proper meaning.
  2. For a data analyst one could only understand that there were 3 classes, but which TP rate is more important was not significant.
  3. Quality thus could have been better of data by elaborationg some information on the Class Attribute.
  4. Quantity and Veracity could have been improved by having some more records of the class Type_H.
